XRD patterns of the different carbon samples are summarized in Fig. 4
                           . For CSs, a broad and high intensity peak at around 22° was observed and this is characteristic of amorphous carbon. For CS0.2 the location did not change while the diffraction peak became weaker and broader, indicating that doping with N does not obviously influence the skeletal structure, however, it became more amorphous. After activation at 900°C, the peak shifted to 24° and a new peak appeared at 44° and this corresponds to 002 and 100 lattice spacings [24]. This is characteristic of a graphite phase while the broad peak indicates a low degree of graphitization. A comparison of the d-spacing (3.7Å) with graphitic ordered carbons (3.4Å) indicates that the interlayer spacing of the nitrogen-doped materials is much larger than that of graphite, this confirms that some N is present in the form of structural N (see Table 3
                           ).
